<div><b><span style="font-size: 24px">Kermsuh (BR-20)</span></b></div>
<div>*updated</div>
<div><b>Status:</b> </div>
<div><br></div>
<div><b><span style="font-size: 18px">Jed's Notes</span></b></div>
<div>This guy shares his experience taking a “shortcut” up and over Hayden/Kettling. Sounds like not really a shortcut, but could be interesting to hike in via Stillwater, then hike out over that shortcut to a waiting shuttle. Probably no net time savings though.<i> </i>Kermsuh &quotshortcut&quot | Backcountry Post<br></div>
<div><br></div>
<div><b><span style="font-size: 18px">Trip Reports</span></b></div>
<div><i>Add trip reports here...</i><br></div>
<div><br></div>
<div>═════════════════════════════════════</div>
<ul>
<li><b>Drainage:</b> Bear River Drainage</li>
<li><b>Elevation:</b> 10300 ft</li>
<li><b>Size:</b> 12.4 acres</li>
<li><b>Max Depth:</b> 14 ft</li>
<li><b>Fishing Pressure:</b> Low</li>
<li><b>Fish Species:</b> Cutthroats</li>
</ul>
<div><br></div>
<div><b><span style="font-size: 18px">Stocking Records</span></b></div>
<div>No stocking records found.</div>
<div><br></div>
<div><b><span style="font-size: 18px">DWR Notes</span></b></div>
<div>Kermsuh is a long, narrow lake situated in rocky timbered country in the isolated West Basin of the Stillwater Fork Drainage. It is 12.4 acres, 10,300 feet in elevation, with 14 feet maximum depth. Campsites are poor due to the rocky nature of the surrounding terrain, but running water is abundant. Horse feed can be located in a small meadow to the south. Access is 1¾ miles south of Christmas Meadows on the Stillwater Pack Trail to the junction with the Kermsuh Lake Trail and then 2¼ miles southwest up the steep grade into West Basin. The cutthroat trout population is sustained by natural reproduction. This lake provides a good opportunity for users seeking solitude.</div>

