<div><b><span style="font-size: 24px">Hell Hole (BR-29)</span></b></div>
<div>d</div>
<div><b>Status:</b> CAUGHT</div>
<div><br></div>
<div><b><span style="font-size: 18px">Jed's Notes</span></b></div>
<div>Can be accessed from Christmas Meadows, or off Mirror Lake Highway. Consensus seems to be take the latter. </div>
<div><br></div>
<div>From Bear River Service, go south on the Mirror Lake Highway about 12 miles to milepost 36.4. The Gold Hill road takes off on the west side here. You want the dirt road slightly north of this taking off on the east. The road is generally passable by all vehicles if carefully driven. Follow it a few hundred yards to where a parking area and closure sign are. This is the shortcut trailhead.</div>
<div>From the road closure sign, follow an old jeep trail that is becoming very overgrown. It crosses Hayden Fork in just a couple of minutes. The old jeep road/trail becomes more faint, but follow it another few minutes to where it crosses a marsh. After crossing the marsh, the trail heads a bit northeast and enters the trees in a couple of minutes. From here it becomes much more defined and easy to follow. About 15-20 minutes from the trailhead you will intersect the road from the Standard Route. Go right here, following the road less than an hour to a bridge. The trail to Hell Hole Lake branches off here on the right (south) on the west side of the bridge.<i>Note: Just north of the bridge, on the west side of the stream, are several old cabin ruins. They are in very dilapidated shape, with only a few logs left standing, but still interesting to visit.</i>From the bridge, the trail leaves the road, goes south and is easy to follow. 10 minutes from the bridge you may notice an old bridge/log flume on the left across the stream. This is a remnant of the early logging days in the area.  It is a bit of a grunt as the trail climb to Hell Hole Lake, but the scenery gets better and better. Most groups will take a couple of hours from the bridge to the lake. There is good camping around the lake, but also anywhere up higher in the basin.</div>
<div><br></div>
<div>(From  https://www.roadtripryan.com/go/t/utah/northern-utah/hell-hole-lake )</div>
<div><br></div>
<div><i>Random guy on Facebook from July 2025</i>: “We knocked out the hike to Hell Hole Lake in 3 hours…I would extremely recommend this trek, fishing the west side of the lake and the mouth of the inlet, as well as the meadow south of the lake.”</div>
<div><br></div>
<div><b><span style="font-size: 18px">Trip Reports</span></b></div>
<div>Sep 26, 2025 Chelsey and I did a day hike in. Plenty of eager small cutthroats. Caught two on gulp minnows showing Chels how to use the spinning rod, then got everything ready to go out on my packraft with new fly rod, and then it started to hail and rain. After a while, I just packed everything up and got ready to leave, and of course, then it stopped raining. :-)</div>
<div><br></div>
<div>═════════════════════════════════════</div>
<ul>
<li><b>Drainage:</b> Bear River Drainage</li>
<li><b>Elevation:</b> 10340 ft</li>
<li><b>Size:</b> 8.5 acres</li>
<li><b>Max Depth:</b> 9 ft</li>
<li><b>Fishing Pressure:</b> Unknown</li>
<li><b>Fish Species:</b> Unknown</li>
</ul>
<div><br></div>
<div><b><span style="font-size: 18px">Stocking Records</span></b></div>
<div>No stocking records found.</div>
